er 12. Kinship and Gender: Property, Enterprise, and Politics -- tChapter 13. Kinship, Civil Society, and Power in Nineteenth-Century Vannes -- tChapter 14. Middle-Class Kinship in Nineteenth-Century Hungary -- tChapter 15. Kinship and Class Dynamics in Nineteenth-Century Europe -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the publication of Philippe Ariès’s book, Centuries of Childhood, in the early 1960s, there has been great interest among historians in the history of the family and the household. A central aspect of the debate relates the story of the family to implicit notions of modernization, with the rise of the nuclear family in the West as part of its economic and political success. During the past decade, however, that synthesis has begun to break down. Historians have begun to examine kinship - the way individual families are connected to each other through marriage and descent - finding that during the most dynamic period in European industrial development, class formation, and state reorganization, Europe became a “kinship hot” society. The essays in this volume explore two major transitions in kinship patterns - at the end of the Middle Ages and at the end of the eighteenth century - in an effort to reset the agenda in family history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aKinshipzEuropexHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aCalvi, Giulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelille, Gérard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerouet, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuhamelle, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, 